we need to do better. obviously, the problem is bigger than just productions, but we must take care to eliminate (or at very least minimize) the harm that we are causing.

thank you @StreetWatchLA for your coverage

i live in dtla, am in community with my unhoused neighbors, and do mutual aid here (i was literally down the block at a sweep defense when this fiasco was going down). as a member of the dtla and film communities, seeing one group of people i love and respect hurt another sucks.
we need to do better at making sure we are not doing harm when we shoot on location. i know there are a million things on the checklist, and adding another is hard, but it is essential.

we should not be doing violence unto our unhoused community and/or endangering their lives to shoot a tv show/movie. it doesn't matter what the scene or project is, or how progressive it is. their suffering is not a fair price for our 'art', nor is it theirs to pay.

A MESSAGE FOR ALL TV PRODUCERS, PARTICULARLY SHOWRUNNERS/EPS:

this morning, an anti-sweep protest scene was shot in DTLA near city hall. in order to make way for the production, a sweep was conducted, displacing unhoused folks. this happens all the time, and it is not okay.

- and then of course there's the distro, managing approximately one million files, title pages, script reports, etc. i'm sure i'm leaving out a zillion things, fellow @IALocal871 SCs please add on!

(btw, the reason i'm able to do that is because my showrunner is fantastic, the bee's knees, and the writers i've had the pleasure of working with are all super receptive. big thank you to them)

((also as far as i can tell, bees knees is not an idiom with a sordid past))

- this might be my own spicy twist, but i flag anything that is or could be interpreted as 'offensive'. slang terms with racist histories (which btw it's hard to find out the etymology of slang), stuff that falls into stereotypes, accidental -isms, you get it.

- when something in a script changes, i make sure the AD team knows ASAP (often before script distro) and outline the production changes that the new pages will cause. i also interface with the script supervisor closely.
- i proof every script. and not just for spelling/grammar, also for continuity of story, timeline, character, language, etc. the higher concept a show is, the more complicated this becomes.
- i track everything. years/timelines, what certain tech is called, if a character mentions they don't like fish, all of it.
- i answer basically any question about scripts, story points, backstory, dialogue, etc. basically if it is on the page or in the show bible, i know it. i track it.

Script coordinators do not make a living wage. Not even close. And we’re at the top end of support staff pay. AND most of us are SCing on top of another job.

Script coordinators and supervisors have an important job, made harder by the fact that it’s only really clear what they’re doing when they’ve done it poorly.
